    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided text from the Significant Accounting Policies and related notes, here is a comprehensive overview of the accounting policies for Property, Plant, and Equipment (PP&E), including specialized aerospace assets.\n\n### **1. General Capitalization & Valuation**\n*   **Cost Basis:** PP&E is stated at cost, less accumulated depreciation.\n*   **Capitalization Criteria:** Costs to acquire, construct, or improve assets are capitalized. This includes parts, labor, and allocated overhead.\n*   **Maintenance vs. Capitalization:** Routine maintenance and repairs are expensed as incurred. Expenditures that increase an asset\'s functionality, output, or expected useful life are capitalized and depreciated over the revised life.\n*   **Interest Capitalization:** Interest costs are capitalized during the construction period for significant long-term projects (e.g., AI data centers). Capitalization begins when activities to prepare the asset commence and ceases when the asset is substantially ready for use. The capitalized interest is included in the asset\'s historical cost.\n\n### **2. Depreciation Methods & Useful Lives**\n*   **General Method:** Depreciation is computed primarily using the **straight-line method** over the estimated useful lives of the assets.\n*   **Exception for Flight Vehicles:** Flight vehicle hardware (boosters, fairings, capsules) and spacecraft are depreciated based on the **expected number of average flights** (a units-of-production method).\n*   **Satellites:** Lives are based on engineering studies considering on-orbit performance, propellant life, and technology evolution.\n    *   Broadband satellites: **5-year** useful life.\n    *   First-generation mobile satellites: **3-year** useful life.\n*   **Leasehold Improvements:** Depreciated over the **shorter of** their estimated useful life or the related lease term.\n*   **Useful Life Schedule:**\n\n| Classification | Estimated Useful Life |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| Servers and networking equipment | 5 - 6 years |\n| Satellites | 3 - 5 years |\n| Machinery and equipment | 3 - 10 years |\n| Flight vehicle hardware | 5 - 25 flights |\n| Data center infrastructure | 20 - 25 years |\n| Launch sites | 7 - 20 years |\n| Buildings and improvements | 30 years |\n| Leasehold improvements | Shorter of 7-20 years or lease term |\n\n### **3. Specialized Asset Policies**\n*   **Launch Vehicles (Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy, Dragon):**\n    *   **Reusable Components** (boosters, fairings, Merlin engines, Dragon capsules): Classified as PP&E and depreciated over expected flights.\n    *   **Expendable Components** (second stages): Treated as **inventory** until launched, at which point cost is recognized in Cost of Revenue.\n*   **Starship:** Currently in development. A majority of costs (test flight hardware, Raptor engines) are **expensed as Research & Development**. Upon commercialization, costs will be capitalized as PP&E and depreciated.\n*   **Satellites:** Capitalized costs include construction (parts, labor, overhead) and allocated launch costs incurred by the Space segment.\n*   **Construction-in-Progress:** Comprises ongoing construction for facilities, equipment, and AI infrastructure not yet placed in service.\n\n### **4. Impairment Policy**\n*   **Trigger:** Assets are reviewed for impairment whenever events or circumstances indicate the carrying value may not be recoverable.\n*   **Level of Assessment:** Evaluated at the lowest level for which identifiable cash flows are largely independent of other assets (the "asset group").\n*   **Recognition:** If estimated future undiscounted cash flows are less than the carrying value, an impairment charge is recorded for the amount by which the carrying value exceeds fair value.\n*   **Presentation:** Routine disposals are typically charged to Cost of Revenue or SG&A. Impairments considered outside normal operations are presented in the "Impairment" line item.\n\n### **5. Accounting for Flight Vehicle Costs**\n*   **Cost of Revenue:** Includes the cost of second stages (inventory), depreciation of reusable components, launch operations, and related overhead.\n*   **Useful Life Estimation for Flight Vehicles:** Based on three key criteria:\n    1.  Ability to successfully recover and refurbish for reuse.\n    2.  Economic feasibility of additional flights (supported by refurbishment cost analyses).\n    3.  Customer acceptance for reflown hardware.\n\n### **6. Key Disclosures & Recent Activity**\n*   **PP&E Growth:** The company has seen significant capital expenditure growth, particularly in servers, satellites, data center infrastructure, and construction-in-progress for AI and expansion projects.\n*   **Capitalized Interest:** Interest was capitalized for major projects like AI data centers (e.g., $169 million in 2025).\n*   **Impairment Charges:** Charges have been recorded for damaged flight vehicles, abandoned production lines, damaged satellite hardware, and facilities consolidation, depending on the segment and nature of the event.\n\n---\n**Summary:** The company\'s PP&E policies reflect its hybrid aerospace and technology operations. Key features include the use of **straight-line depreciation** for most assets, with a **units-of-flight depreciation method** for reusable launch vehicles, and specific capitalization rules for satellites and major construction projects. The policies require significant management judgment in estimating useful lives, expected flights, and impairment triggers.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=25.631,
    error=None,
