    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output="Based on the provided text from the Significant Accounting Policies note and related MD&A sections, here is a summary of the accounting policies for research and development (R&D) costs:\n\n### General R&D Expense Policy\nThe company expenses R&D costs as incurred. These expenses include:\n*   Materials, employee compensation (salaries, benefits, share-based compensation), contractor costs.\n*   Cloud computing, data services, equipment leases, depreciation of R&D equipment, and allocated overhead.\n*   Certain expenses for features/modules developed through engineering services where the company retains the IP.\n\n### Software Development Costs\n*   Software development costs marketed under on-premise perpetual license agreements are expensed.\n*   Costs incurred prior to technological feasibility are expensed as R&D.\n*   **Key Policy Point:** Technological feasibility typically occurs shortly before general release. Therefore, **all software development costs for the years 2023, 2024, and 2025 were expensed as incurred** (i.e., no software costs were capitalized during these periods).\n\n### Segment-Specific R&D Treatments\n\n**1.  Space Segment (Starship):**\n*   R&D expenses primarily relate to Starship development, build, and testing. These costs (including test hardware, Raptor engines, compensation, tooling, etc.) are **expensed as incurred** during the current development stage.\n*   **Anticipated Future Change:** Once Starship is commercialized (delivering payload to orbit), its costs are generally expected to be **capitalized and then depreciated in cost of revenue**.\n\n**2.  Connectivity Segment (Satellites, Starlink):**\n*   R&D expenses relate to next-generation satellites, Starlink Kits, and ground infrastructure.\n*   **Capitalization Policy:** The cost to build satellites and capitalized launch costs are recorded as **Property, Plant & Equipment** and depreciated. However, the associated **R&D costs for their development are expensed**.\n\n**3.  AI Segment:**\n*   R&D expenses relate to training Grok models, developing next-gen AI products, and associated data center costs (including cloud computing, compensation, and depreciation of GPU hardware).\n*   These costs are **expensed as incurred**.\n\n### Capitalization of Assets (Related to R&D Output)\nWhile R&D is expensed, assets resulting from successful R&D are capitalized under specific policies:\n*   **Property, Plant & Equipment (PP&E):** Capitalized at cost less depreciation. This includes reusable spacecraft (Falcon boosters, Dragon), satellites, and general equipment. Depreciation methods are straight-line or based on expected flights for flight vehicles.\n*   **Satellites:** Include building costs (parts, labor, overhead) and capitalized launch costs.\n*   **Interest Capitalization:** Interest costs associated with significant construction of PP&E is capitalized from the start of construction until the asset is substantially ready for use.\n\n### Summary of R&D Capitalization vs. Expense\n| **R&D Activity / Asset** | **Accounting Treatment** | **Key Condition / Note** |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **General R&D** | Expensed as incurred | Policy states all R&D is expensed. |\n| **Software Development** | Expensed as incurred | Technological feasibility occurs just before release, leading to no capitalization in recent years. |\n| **Starship (Space)** | Expensed as incurred | Currently in development stage. **Will shift to capitalization upon commercialization.** |\n| **Satellite & Kit Development** | Expensed as incurred | R&D for development is expensed. The manufactured satellites are capitalized as PP&E. |\n| **Grok/AI Model Training** | Expensed as incurred | Includes cloud computing, compensation, and GPU depreciation. |\n| **Capitalizable PP&E & Satellites** | Capitalized & Depreciated | Successful R&D outputs (e.g., flight vehicles, satellites) are capitalized once ready for use. |\n\n**In essence, the company's current policy is to expense virtually all R&D costs as incurred. The most notable exception anticipated in the disclosures is the future capitalization of Starship costs once the vehicle moves from the development stage to commercial service.**",
