    tool_call=ToolCall(
        id='call_0ef7e4a977b54260a8533c4d',
        call_id=None,
        name='retrieve_information',
        args='{"prompt": "Retrieve any disclosure about orbital compute satellites, AI compute satellites, Starlink satellite asset treatment, satellite constellations, and how satellites are capitalized or depreciated in {{spacex_s1}}."}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'Retrieve any disclosure about orbital compute satellites, AI compute satellites, Starlink satellite asset treatment, satellite constellations, and how satellites are capitalized or depreciated in {{spacex_s1}}.'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Disclosures on Orbital AI Compute Satellites, Starlink Satellite Asset Treatment, and Satellite Capitalization/Depreciation\n\nBelow is a consolidated retrieval of the relevant disclosures from the provided document chunks, organized by topic.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Orbital AI Compute Satellites\n\n### Strategic Vision and Deployment Timeline\nThe company plans to deploy **orbital AI compute satellites** designed to handle energy-intensive AI workloads (such as inference demand) in **Sun-synchronous orbit** at far greater scale and efficiency than terrestrial alternatives. Starlink will provide low-latency, global connectivity linking these orbital AI systems to end users. **Deployment is expected as early as 2028.**\n\n> *"satellites in Sun-synchronous orbit will be able to handle energy-intensive AI workloads, such as inference demand, at far greater scale and efficiency than terrestrial alternatives, with Starlink providing low-latency, global connectivity linking these orbital AI systems to people around the world and delivering real-time intelligence. We expect to begin deploying our orbital AI compute satellites as early as 2028."*\n\n### Technical Design\nThe AI compute satellites are expected to **leverage the already-designed V3 satellite platform**, with substantially more power generated through significantly larger solar arrays — approximately **five times the solar array output** compared to V3 satellite designs. They are targeted to generate approximately **100 kW of compute power per ton**. No significant on-orbit assembly is currently contemplated.\n\n### Competitive Positioning\nThe company states it believes it is **"the only company with a commercially viable path to building orbital AI compute at scale,"** underpinned by its ability to:\n- Launch substantial mass into orbit cost-efficiently through **reusable rockets** (Starship)\n- Manufacture secure, reliable, high-performance satellites at **low cost and high volume**\n- Deploy a **modular shell approach** built around its scalable satellite constellation\n\n> *"We plan to develop orbital data centers to enable scaling of compute capacity for us and our customers that is independent of terrestrial power infrastructure constraints. Space offers the potential to access virtually limitless power and an operating environment that supports sustained high-density compute, including structural advantages for power generation, cooling, and uninterrupted operations as capacity grows."*\n\n### Operational Strategy for AI Compute Satellites\nThe company plans to build on its experience operating ~9,600 Starlink satellites in LEO, including:\n- **Automated collision avoidance** (over 1,000 maneuvers/day in 2025)\n- **Thermal management**: solar arrays facing the sun for constant power; radiator panels facing deep space for radiative cooling\n- **Lifecycle management**: shifting older hardware to lower-intensity workloads, retiring systems through controlled end-of-life disposition (including graveyard orbits)\n- Retirements **"may occur sooner than our estimates for the useful lives of our satellites"**\n\n### Risk Factors\nThe forward-looking disclosures warn that:\n- The deployment of orbital AI compute infrastructure is subject to **significant technical complexity, capital requirements, new innovations, and regulatory approvals**\n- These investments may result in **"periods of reduced profitability or increased losses"** as the company prioritizes long-term growth\n\n### Use of IPO Proceeds\nNet proceeds are intended to fund:\n- Expansion of **AI compute infrastructure**\n- Enhancements to **launch infrastructure and launch vehicles**\n- Increases in the **scale and capacity of satellite constellations**\n- General corporate purposes\n\n### Capital Expenditure Expectations\nThe company discloses that it has incurred and expects to **substantially increase** capital expenditures for satellite constellations, launch vehicles, ground stations, manufacturing facilities, **AI compute infrastructure, data centers**, and other supporting infrastructure. This includes costs for obtaining third-party GPUs, manufacturing its own GPUs, and constructing/leasing/maintaining data centers.\n\n### Inter-Segment Launch Capacity Allocation\nThe company allocates significant launch capacity to its **Connectivity segment** for Starlink satellite deployment, and **"expect[s] to allocate a significant amount to our AI segment in the future."** These internal launches do not generate inter-segment revenue; instead, launch costs are capitalized.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Starlink Satellite Asset Treatment\n\n### Capitalization of Starlink Satellite Launches\nFor launches of Starlink satellites, the company **does not recognize any inter-segment revenue**. Instead, launch costs are **capitalized in satellites** within **"Property, plant, and equipment, net."**\n\n> *"For launches of our Starlink satellites, the Company does not recognize any inter-segment revenue, rather those launch costs are capitalized in satellites in Property, plant, and equipment, net."*\n\n### Inter-Segment Cost Flow\nWhen the Space segment dedicates launch capacity to deploying Starlink satellites, the associated costs are **capitalized within the Connectivity segment** and depreciated over time. No revenue is recognized in the Space segment for these launches.\n\n> *"dedicated to deploying our Starlink satellites, we capitalize the associated costs within our Connectivity segment and depreciate them over time, and we do not recognize revenue for those launches in our Space segment."*\n\n### Starlink Constellation Scale\nAs of March 31, 2026:\n- ~**9,600 Starlink broadband and mobile satellites** in Low-Earth Orbit\n- ~**10.3 million Starlink Subscribers** across 164 countries\n- ~**7.4 million monthly unique devices** for satellite-to-mobile services across ~30 countries\n- Over **23,000 inter-satellite lasers** creating a dynamic mesh network in space\n\n### Impairment of Starlink/Connectivity Assets\nFor the years ended December 31, 2025 and 2024, impairment charges of **$38 million** and **$63 million** respectively were recorded, related to write-offs of:\n- Damaged flight vehicle in the **Space segment**\n- Abandoned production line and **damaged satellite hardware in the Connectivity segment**\n\n---\n\n## 3. Satellite Capitalization and Depreciation Policies\n\n### What Is Capitalized in Satellite Assets\nSatellites include:\n- **Costs to build the satellites** (parts, labor, and allocated overhead)\n- **Capitalized launch costs** incurred by the Space segment to launch satellites to orbit, including **an allocation of the flight vehicle**\n\n> *"Satellites include costs to build the satellites (parts, labor, and allocated overhead) as well as capitalized launch costs incurred by the Space segment to launch the satellites to orbit, which include an allocation of the flight vehicle"*\n\n### Interest Capitalization\nThe company capitalizes certain interest costs associated with significant acquisition or construction of qualifying assets (including **AI infrastructure data centers**):\n- Capitalization begins once activities necessary to get the asset ready for its intended use have commenced\n- Uses the **average accumulated expenditures** and a **capitalization rate derived from the weighted average borrowing rate**\n- For the year ended December 31, 2025: **$169 million** of interest was capitalized (included in Construction-in-progress)\n- **No interest was capitalized** during the years ended December 31, 2024 and 2023\n\n### Depreciation Methods\n- Most assets: **straight-line method** over estimated useful lives\n- **Flight vehicles**: computed based on the **expected number of average flights** for each flight vehicle\n- Leasehold improvements: depreciated over the **shorter of estimated useful lives or the related lease term**\n- Management periodically reviews useful life estimates with engineering and operations teams\n\n### Useful Lives of Satellite Assets\nThe company estimates useful lives based on:\n- Engineering studies\n- Historical on-orbit performance\n- Propellant life\n- Utilization patterns\n- Design enhancements across generations\n- Planned transitions to newer satellite technology\n\nSpecific useful lives:\n| Asset Type | Estimated Useful Life |\n|---|---|\n| **Broadband satellites** | **5 years** |\n| **First-generation mobile satellites** | **3 years** |\n\n### Flight Vehicle Depreciation Criteria\nExpected flights for flight vehicle hardware are based on three criteria:\n1. Continued ability to successfully **recover and refurbish** the hardware\n2. Continued **economic feasibility** of incremental flights, supported by declining refurbishment costs and sensitivity analyses\n3. **Customer acceptance** for reflown hardware\n\n### Maintenance vs. Capitalization\n- **Maintenance and repairs** that do not extend asset lives → **expensed as incurred**\n- **Significant refurbishment, renewals, and enhancements** that increase functionality, output, or expected life → **capitalized and depreciated ratably** over the identified useful life\n\n### Depreciation Expense\nFor the years ended December 31:\n| Year | Depreciation Expense |\n|---|---|\n| **2025** | **$5,915 million** |\n| **2024** | **$2,977 million** |\n| **2023** | *(not specified in provided text)* |\n\n### Construction-in-Progress\nConstruction in progress is primarily comprised of ongoing construction and expansion of facilities and equipment, as well as **AI infrastructure that has not yet been placed in service**.\n\n### Impairment Evaluation\nThe company evaluates impairment of Property, plant, and equipment at the **lowest level for which identifiable cash flows are largely independent** of the cash flows of other assets and liabilities.\n\n### Reusable Flight Vehicle Classification\n- **Boosters, fairings, and Merlin engines** → classified as **Property, plant, and equipment, net** (reusable)\n- **Second stages** → classified as **inventory** (not reusable) until launched or assigned\n- **Dragon capsule** → classified as **Property, plant, and equipment, net** (fully reusable)\n- **Starship** → currently in development; a majority of Starship costs are **expensed to Research and development** as incurred\n\n---\n\n## 4. Satellite Constellations — Summary of Capital and Operational Scale\n\nThe company\'s capital expenditure strategy is deeply tied to its constellation deployment model:\n- IPO proceeds are directed toward **increases in the scale and capacity of satellite constellations**\n- The **Space segment funds R&D** that benefits Connectivity and AI segments: $930M (Q1 2026) and $3,004M (FY 2025)\n- The **Space segment\'s financial results do not reflect the strategic value** it provides to Connectivity and AI through internal launches\n- Deployment of 100 GW/year of orbital AI compute via satellites carrying **over 100 kW of compute per metric ton** will require **thousands of launches/year** and transport of approximately **one million metric tons to orbit annually**',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=31.3,
