 to the asset\'s cost in CIP. For example, $7 million was capitalized in Q1 2026. This capitalized interest is depreciated over the asset\'s useful life.\n    *   **Depreciation:** Once an asset is placed in service, it is depreciated on a straight-line basis over its estimated useful life. Depreciation expense is recognized in the income statement, primarily within **Research and development** and **Cost of revenue** segments. For the AI segment, this includes depreciation of GPU hardware and data center assets.\n\n2.  **Impairment:**\n    *   The company evaluates PP&E for impairment at the lowest level for which identifiable cash flows are largely independent.\n    *   **Space Segment:** Impairment charges have been recorded for damaged flight vehicles (e.g., $24 million in Q1 2025).\n    *   **AI Segment:** Historically, impairment charges were recorded as part of **Restructuring charges** related to facilities consolidation (e.g., $36 million in 2024). More recently, AI segment Adjusted EBITDA declines are driven by heavy investment in compute infrastructure, but no specific PP&E impairment was noted for the AI segment in the most recent periods provided.\n\n### **Strategic & Operational Context**\nThe financial notes confirm that the AI segment\'s strategy involves **extreme capital expenditure** in compute infrastructure. This is directly reflected in:\n*   The rapidly growing **Servers and networking equipment** (GPU hardware) and **Construction-in-progress** balances.\n*   The development and planned deployment of **orbital AI compute satellites**, which are classified as satellites but serve a dual-purpose for communications and AI compute.\n*   The company\'s disclosure that it expects a "multi-year investment horizon" before its terrestrial and orbital data center deployments translate into sustained profitability for the AI segment.\n\nIn summary, the company capitalizes the costs of its AI infrastructure (GPUs, data centers, compute satellites) as PP&E, depreciates them over their useful lives, and capitalizes related interest costs during construction. The significant and growing CIP balance highlights the ongoing, large-scale investment in this segment.',
